type(text[0]) # langchain_core.documents.base.Document

whenever we work with long chain, it tries to convert everything into a document type.
Because if we try to convert a text into a document type, we will have more features which we can specifically implement.

======= Recursive Character Text Splitter ======
How to split by character-character text Splitter?

This is the simplest method. This splits based on a given character sequence, which defaults to "\n\n". Chunk length is measured by number of characters.

. How the text is split: by single character seperator
. How the chunk size is measured : by number of characters

from langchain_community.document_loaders import TextLoader

loader = TextLoader('speech.txt')
docs = loader.load()
docs

from langchain_text_splitters import CharacterTextSplitter
text_splitter = CharacterTextSplitter(seperator="\n\n",chunk_size=100,chunk_overlap=20)
text_splitter.split_documents(docs)

#"Created a chunk of size 470, which is longer than the specified 100"
#"Created a chunk of size 347, which is longer than the specified 100"
#"Created a chunk of size 668, which is longer than the specified 100"

When we run this, it says "Created a chunk of size 470, which is longer than the specified 100". The reason is, it is not able to find the seperator.
Wherever it was able to find the seperator based on that it has created the chunk size.

If we are not giving the seperator, then by-default it will be "\n\n".

from langchain_community.document_loaders import TextLoader

loader = TextLoader('speech.txt')
docs = loader.load()
docs

speech=""
with open("speech.txt") as f:
	speech.f.read()
	
from langchain_text_splitters import CharacterTextSplitter

text_splitter= CharacterTextSplitter(chunk_size=100,chunk_overlap=20)
text=text_splitter.create_documents([speech])
print(text[0])
print(text[1])

Q) Which one should we use? RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter or CharacterTextSplitter ?
-> whenever you have an opportunity you have a choice from this particular two that you want to select.Go ahead with RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter.

====== HTML Text Splitter ========
We have a library HTMLHeaderTextSplitter.

It is a "structured-aware" Chunk that splits text at HTML elements level and adds metadata for each header "relevant" to any given chunk.
It can return chunk elements by element, or combine elements with the same metadata with the objective of 
(a) keeping related text grouped (more or less) semantically 
(b) preserving context rich information encoded in the document structure.
It can be use with other text_splitters as part of the chunking pipeline.

from langchain_text_splitters import HTMLHeaderTextSplitter

html_string = """
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
<h1></h1>
<div></div>
<div></div>
<br>
<p></p>
</body>
</html>
"""

headers_to_split_on=[("h1","Header 1"),("hw","Header 2"),("h3","Header 3")]
html_splitter= HTMLHeaderTextSplitter(headers_to_split_on=headers_to_split_on)
html_header_splits= html_splitter.split_text(html_string)
html_header_splits #It is of document type. In the metadata you will see, how the text is splitted between Headers.


ANOTHER EXAMPLE :
url ="https://plato.standford.edu/entries/geodel/"

headers_to_split_on=[("h1","Header 1"),("hw","Header 2"),("h3","Header 3")]
html_splitter2= HTMLHeaderTextSplitter(headers_to_split_on=headers_to_split_on)
html_splitter2


===== Recursive JSON Text Splitter =======
Q) How to split the JSON data?
this JSON splitter splits JSON data while allowing control over chunk sizes.It traverses JSON data depth first and builds smaller JSON chunks.
It attempts to keep nested JSON objects whole, but will split them if needed to keep chunks between a minimum chunk size and the maximum chunk size.

If the value is not a nested JSON, but rather a very large string, the string will not be split. 
If you need a hard cap on the chunk size, consider composing this with a recursive text character splitter. there is an optional pre-processing step to split list by first converting them into JSON dictionary and then splitting them first.

	. How the text is splited : based pn JSON value
	. How the chunk size is measured : by number of characters
	
	

import json
import requests

json_data = request.get("https://api.smith.langchain.com/openapi.json").json()

from langchain_text_splitters import RecursiveJsonSplitter
json_splitter = RecursiveJsonSplitter(max_chunk_size=300)
json_chunks=json_splitter.split_json(json_data)

for chunk in json_chunks:
	print(chunks)
	
# The splitter can also output documents
docs = json_splitter.create_documents(text=[json_data])
for doc in docs[:3]:
	print(doc)
	
#If you don't want it in document, then we can split it into texts.
texts=json_splitter.split(json_data)
print(texts[0))
print(texts[1])


